{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538406"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:27:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:27:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16170"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17610463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17610463"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:01:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:01:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16170"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16170"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.13,0.23,0.53,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8861"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64198"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8861"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16170"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49630"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2382"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21107"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44562"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64198"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department four hours after accidentally spilling cleaning agent containing sodium hypochlorite (alkali) onto his right forearm. He reports redness and tenderness over the affected area. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as a cleaner and is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His right forearm shows a 10 x 4 cm area of erythema. The emergency physician is concerned about a significant chemical burn and initiates resuscitation and referral to a burns unit.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of an alkali burn?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Coagulative necrosis with cessation of injury after removal of agent","Liquefactive necrosis with cessation of injury after removal of agent","Coagulative necrosis with ongoing injury despite removal of agent","Liquefactive necrosis with ongoing injury despite removal of agent","Caseous necrosis with cessation of injury after removal of agent"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAlkali burns are particularly destructive due to their mechanism of tissue injury. \u003Cstrong\u003ELiquefactive necrosis with ongoing injury despite removal of agent\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of alkali burns. Alkalis cause tissue destruction through saponification of fats and denaturation of proteins, which allows deep penetration into tissues. The process continues even after the chemical has been removed or neutralised, leading to progressive tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoagulative necrosis with cessation of injury after removal of agent\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of acid burns. Acids typically cause immediate tissue damage through protein denaturation, forming an eschar that limits further penetration. The injury usually stops once the acid is removed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiquefactive necrosis with cessation of injury after removal of agent\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because alkali burns continue to cause damage even after removal of the chemical due to ongoing saponification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoagulative necrosis with ongoing injury despite removal of agent\u003C/strong\u003E combines incorrect elements of both processes and does not accurately describe either acid or alkali burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaseous necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with tuberculosis and other granulomatous conditions, not chemical burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of chemical burns includes immediate copious irrigation with water, pain management, tetanus prophylaxis if indicated, and early referral to a burns unit. The extent of tissue damage may not be immediately apparent due to the progressive nature of alkali burns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alkali burns cause liquefactive necrosis through saponification of fats and protein denaturation.","Alkali burns continue to cause tissue damage even after the chemical has been removed.","Initial management of chemical burns includes copious irrigation and early referral to a burns unit."],"references":["Gnaneswaran N, Perera E, Perera M, Sawhney R. Cutaneous chemical burns: assessment and early management. Aust Fam Physician. 2015 Mar;44(3):135-9. PMID: 25770579."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49630"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16170"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49630"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T07:14:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T07:15:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8861"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64198"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":